[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"service": "Orthopedics", "current": 28, "proposed": 34, "change": "+6", "reason": "Two new surgeons, 3-week backlog"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"service": "Cardiac Surgery", "current": 24, "proposed": 20, "change": "-4", "reason": "Volume decline post-retirement"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"service": "General Surgery", "current": 20, "proposed": 22, "change": "+2", "reason": "Consistent overflow"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"service": "Neurosurgery", "current": 16, "proposed": 16, "change": "0", "reason": "Demand matches allocation"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"service": "Urology", "current": 12, "proposed": 14, "change": "+2", "reason": "Growing robotic program"}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Solve time (20 ORs, quarterly) | 30–120 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Solve time (40 ORs, quarterly) | 2–15 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Optimality gap achieved | < 1% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Utilization improvement | 8–15 percentage points |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Revenue impact (mid-size hospital) | $2–8M annually |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Block release reallocation time | < 5 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Demand forecast accuracy (MAPE) | 10–20% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Hospitals with highly political allocation processes where mathematical optimality is overridden by relationship dynamics. Situations where demand forecasting is unreliable (new programs with no history, post-pandemic volume uncertainty). Very large academic medical centers with 50+ ORs and complex subspecialty requirements that push solve times into hours.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's what nobody tells you about OR block scheduling optimization: the math is the easy part. Getting a solver to produce an optimal schedule takes a few weeks of engineering. Getting a hospital to actually implement that schedule takes 6-12 months of political negotiation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The first time you run the optimizer and it says "cardiac surgery should lose 4 blocks," you'll learn very quickly that the chief of cardiac surgery sits on the hospital board. Your mathematically optimal solution needs to survive a committee meeting. Build in change limits (no service loses more than X% per cycle) and present results as recommendations, not mandates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The demand forecasting piece is where most implementations underperform. Trailing averages miss structural changes (new surgeon hires, program launches). But sophisticated forecasting models need data that hospitals often don't have in clean, accessible form. Start simple (12-month trailing average with manual adjustments for known changes) and add complexity only when the simple model demonstrably fails.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The block release mechanism is actually where you get the fastest ROI. Most hospitals have 15-25% of blocks going unused in any given week. Just getting those released and reallocated (even with simple rules, no optimization required) can improve utilization by 5-8 percentage points. Build that first, prove value, then tackle the harder quarterly reallocation problem.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m One thing that surprised me: the constraint that matters most isn't equipment or staffing. It's surgeon preference patterns. Surgeons are creatures of habit. They want their same day, same OR, same start time. Disrupting that pattern (even for a mathematically better schedule) creates friction that can tank adoption. Weight "schedule stability" heavily in your objective function, at least for the first few optimization cycles.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Stochastic optimization for demand uncertainty.** Instead of optimizing against point forecasts, formulate a stochastic program that considers multiple demand scenarios. The solution is robust across scenarios rather than optimal for one. This matters when demand is volatile (post-pandemic recovery, new market entrants). The tradeoff: stochastic formulations are harder to solve and harder to explain to stakeholders.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-objective optimization with Pareto frontiers.** Rather than collapsing utilization, revenue, equity, and surgeon satisfaction into a single weighted objective, solve the multi-objective problem and present the Pareto frontier to decision-makers. "Here are the tradeoffs: you can have 85% utilization with moderate equity, or 78% utilization with perfect equity. Which do you prefer?" This makes the tradeoffs explicit rather than hiding them in weight choices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Rolling horizon with learning.** Instead of a fixed quarterly cycle, implement a rolling optimization that adjusts allocations monthly based on actual utilization vs. forecast. Services that consistently underutilize their blocks gradually lose time; services with overflow gradually gain it. This reduces the political shock of large quarterly changes and creates a continuous improvement dynamic.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.1 (Appointment Slot Optimization):** Optimizes at the clinic scheduling level; complementary to OR block scheduling for outpatient surgical procedures
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.4 (Nurse Staffing Optimization):** Staffing constraints feed directly into OR block scheduling; the two should be co-optimized or at least coordinated
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 14.7 (OR Case Sequencing):** Operates within the blocks allocated by this recipe; optimizes the day-of case order within a given block
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.5 (Hospital Census Forecasting):** Downstream surgical volume affects inpatient census; block schedule changes should inform census forecasts
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 7.7 (Length of Stay Prediction):** Post-surgical LOS predictions help forecast downstream bed demand from OR schedule changes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
